      <hedline>
        <hl1>Digital Limits</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert J Gilliard letter on May 11 article warns use of virtual orchestra is not likely to be limited to supporting touring groups and small ensembles that cannot afford orchestra</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Digitally Sampled Sounds Are Filling Out Some Orchestra Pits'' (May 11) seems to show that some people are on a high-speed quest to a totally technological society. But there are cultural things that do not benefit from technological efficiencies.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Digitally Sampled Sounds Are Filling Out Some Orchestra Pits'' (May 11) seems to show that some people are on a high-speed quest to a totally technological society. But there are cultural things that do not benefit from technological efficiencies.</p>
        <p>If this application were limited to the stated purpose -- supporting touring groups and small ensembles that otherwise could not afford an orchestra -- that might be acceptable. But often such systems are not self-limiting.</p>
        <p>ROBERT J. GILLIARD  Cambria Heights, N.Y.</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the electro-acoustics division at Sound Advice Associates.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
